<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25180b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25180b">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25180b"> 180(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sakti</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The Montanists in Phrygia in the second century held &ldquo;revivalist&rdquo; meetings exactly like those of the Welsh to-day, or of the Moslems in Persia, and the negroes in America. The immoral meetings of the Adamites, among Christians, are indistinguishable from the Bacchic orgies which were forbidden by horror-stricken Romans in 186 B.C., or from the vile rites of existing <mark>Sakti</mark> sects in India. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 160</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Shakti (Sanskrit <i>Sakti</i>): the female principle or organ of generative power; derivatively, the wife of a deity, especially of Shiva.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14121e" href="c14all.htm#c14121e">VI.C.14:121(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
